column2: DER Profile Version Number.  Always the number 1.00 for this specification.
DER Profile Implementation Level. 1 2 or 3 to indicate support for Level 1 Level 2 or Level 3 respectively.
Nameplate Active Generation Power Rating at Unity Power Factor
Nameplate Active Charging Power Rating at Unity Power Factor
Nameplate Active Generation Power Rating at Specified Over-Excited Power Factor
Nameplate Active Charging Power Rating at Specified Over-Excited Power Factor
Nameplate Active Generation Power Rating at Specified Under-Excited Power Factor
Nameplate Active Charging Power Rating at Specified Under-Excited Power Factor
Storage Effective Actual Energy Capacity. Present actual total energy expressed in Storage Capacity Units.
Storage Usable Energy Capacity. Usable energy capacity of the storage system expressed in Storage Capacity Units.
Nameplate AC Current Maximum Generation Rating
Nameplate AC Current Maximum Charging Rating Remaining Reactive Susceptance
IEEE 1547 Normal Operating Performance Category.  Enumeration:
IEEE 1547 Abnormal Operating Performance Category.  Enumeration: <0> unknown <1> Category I <2> Category II <3> Category III
Number of DER units connected to controller
Open Loop Response Time Percentage.  Percent of target to reach within the open loop response time. Default is 90%.
Power Factor Sign Convention: <1>  IEC: active power <2> IEEE: lead/lag
System Available Actual State of Charge - Currently available energy in the storage system as a percentage of Nameplate Storage Actual Capacity.
System Available Usable State of Charge - Currently usable energy in the storage system as a percentage of Nameplate Storage Usable Capacity.
DER Start (Return to Service) Voltage High Limit. Percent of Reference Voltage.
DER Start (Return to Service) Voltage Low Limit. Percent of Reference Voltage.
DER Start (Return to Service) Frequency High Limit
DER Start (Return to Service) Frequency Low Limit
DER Start (Return to Service) Time Window
DER Start (Return to Service) Ramp Up Time
DER Stop (Cease to Energize) Time Window
DER Stop (Cease to Energize) Ramp Down Time
DER Stop (Cease to Energize) Reversion Timeout Period . Time to revert from the stopped state and return to service.
Connect/Disconnect Reversion Timeout Period . Timeout (reversion time is for the Disconnect only)
Maximum Generation Ramp Up Rate. The maximum generation ramp up rate expressed as a percentage of the Maximum Generation Rate (WMax) per second.
Maximum Generation Ramp Down Rate. The maximum generation ramp down rate expressed as a percentage of the Maximum Generation Rate (WMax) per second.
Maximum Charging Ramp Up Rate. The maximum charging ramp up rate expressed as a percentage of the Maximum Charging Rate (WChaMax) per second.
Maximum Charging Ramp Down Rate. The maximum charging ramp down rate expressed as a percentage of the Maximum Charnging Rate (WChaMax) per second.

Requested Settings Group. Enumeration: <0> Not Used <1> Unspecified / Autonomously Determined (see BO Enable Sensed Grid Config Detection) <2> Factory Configuration <3> Default Configuration / Comms Lost <4> Normal Grid Connected Configuration <5> Islanded Condition 1 (small local island) <6> Islanded Condition 2 (larger area island)

Settings Group Being Edited.Enumeration: <0> Not Used <1> Unspecified / Autonomously Determined (see BO Enable Sensed Grid Config Detection) <2> Factory Configuration <3> Default Configuration / Comms Lost <4> Normal Grid-Connected Configuration <5> Islanded Condition 1 (small local island) <6> Islanded Condition 2 (larger area island) <7> Islanded Condition 3 (largest regional island <8> 1st Alternate Grid-Connected Configuration <9> 2nd Alternate Grid-Connected Configuration <10> 3rd Alternate Grid-Connected Configuration <11-255> Reserved for future assignment

Active Settings Group.  Note this may differ from the Requested Settings Group or Settings Group Being Edited analog outputs depending on whether communications has been lost and how the Enable Sensed Grid Config Detection binary output is set. <0> Not Used <1> Unspecified / Autonomously Determined (see BO42) <2> Factory Configuration <3> Default Configuration / Comms Lost <4> Normal Grid-Connected Configuration <5> Islanded Condition 1 (small local island) <6> Islanded Condition 2 (larger area island) <7> Islanded Condition 3 (largest regional island) <8> 1st Alternate Grid-Connected Configuration <9> 2nd Alternate Grid-Connected Configuratio <10> 3rd Alternate Grid-Connected Configuration <11-255> Reserved for future assignment
Freeze Counter Interval. Interval between freeze counter operations after the initial occurrence.  A zero value means the free counter operation is not repeated.
Freeze Counter Interval Units. Units of the interval between freeze counter operations.  See reference for values.
Low/High Voltage Ride-Through Signal Meter ID.  Referenced ECP.  This is the meter from which current is being read to evaluate and provide support.
Low/High Voltage Ride-Through Voltage Reference Input.  Active voltage measurement read from the meter and used as an input to the mode.
Low/High Voltage Ride-Through High Must Trip Curve Index.  Index of the Voltage Ride-through curve which specifies trip points when the voltage is high.
Low/High Voltage Ride-Through Low Must Trip Curve Index.  Index of the Voltage Ride-through curve which specifies trip points when the voltage is low.
Low/High Voltage Ride-Through High Momentary Cessation Curve Index. Index of the Voltage Ride-through curve which specifies where generation / discharging must stop when the voltage is high.
Low/High Voltage Ride-Through Low Momentary Cessation Curve Index. Index of the Voltage Ride-through curve which specifies where generation / discharging must stop when the voltage is low.
Low/High Frequency Ride-Through Signal Meter ID.  Referenced ECP. This is the meter from which current is being read to evaluate and provide support.
Low/High Frequency Ride-Through Frequency Reference Input.  Active frequency measurement read from the meter and used as an input to the mode.
Low/High Frequency Ride-Through High Must Trip Curve Index.  Index of the Frequency Ride-through curve which specifies trip points when the frequency is high.
Low/High Frequency Ride-Through Low Must Trip Curve Index.  Index of the Frequency Ride-through curve which specifies trip points when the frequency is low.
Low/High Frequency Ride-Through High Momentary Cessation Curve Index.  Index of the Frequency Ride-through curve which specifies where generation / discharging must stop when the frequency is high.
Low/High Frequency Ride-Through Low Momentary Cessation Curve Index.  Index of the Frequency Ride-through curve which specifies  where generation / discharging must stop when the frequencyf is low.
Dynamic Reactive Current Support Mode Priority
Dynamic Reactive Current Support Enabling Time Window
Dynamic Reactive Current Support Enabling Ramp Time
Dynamic Reactive Current Support Timeout Period
Dynamic Reactive Current Support Signal Meter ID.  Referenced ECP. This is the meter from which current is being read to evaluate and provide support.
Dynamic Reactive Current Support Moving Average Voltage

Dynamic Reactive Current Support Present Delta Voltage.  Difference in Volts between the present measured Voltage and the Moving Average Voltage (RDGS.Vav) as a percentage of the reference voltage (VRef)
Dynamic Reactive Current Support - Gradient Mode.  Enumeration: <0> Undefined <1> Gradients reach 0 at the moving average Voltage <2> Gradients reach 0 at the Voltage deadband

Dynamic Reactive Current Support Deadband Minimum Voltage. Percentage of the nominal voltage (DRCT.Vref) measured from the moving average voltage (RDGS.VAv). Support is no longer applied when the voltage stays above this value for the length of the Hold Time.

Dynamic Reactive Current Support Deadband Maximum Voltage. Percentage of the nominal voltage (DRCT.Vref) measured from the moving average voltage (RDGS.VAv). Support is no longer applied when the voltage stays below this value for the length of the Hold Time.

Dynamic Reactive Current Support Gradient for Sags.  Percentage of the rated current (DRAT.ARtg) to apply capacitively per percentage of the negative deviation from the moving "average voltage (RDGS.Av).   It is a ratio of percent and is therefore unitless."

Dynamic Reactive Current Support Gradient for Swells.  Percentage of the rated current (DRAT.ARtg) to apply inductively per percentage of the positive deviation from the moving average voltage (RDGS.Av).   It is a ratio of percent and is therefore unitless.
Dynamic Reactive Current Support Filter Time for Moving Average Voltage (RDGS.VAv).  Used to determine amount of dynamic reactive current support.
Dynamic Reactive Current Support Block Zone Voltage.  Percentage of the nominal voltage (DRCT.VRef) below which no reactive current support shall be applied.

Dynamic Reactive Current Support Hysteresis Block Zone Voltage. Percentage of the nominal voltage (DRCT.VRef).   After being blocked reactive current support shall not resume until the voltage has been above BlkZnV + HysBlkZnV.

Dynamic Reactive Current Support Block Zone Time. Time in milliseconds from the beginning of any "sag" event before which dynamic reactive current support will always continue regardless of how low voltage may sag.

Dynamic Reactive Current Support Hold Time.   When the voltage returns to within the deadband limits (RDGS.dbVMin annd RDGS.dbVMax) "for this length of time (measured in milliseconds) the ""sag"" or ""swell"" event is considered to be over. Reactive current support ends frozen values are unfrozen and a new event can begin."
Dynamic Reactive Current Attempted Output. Current output that the mode is attempting to achieve based on the Voltage  input and other parameters.
Dynamic Volt-Watt Voltage Reference Input.  Votltage measurement read from the meter and used as an input to the mode.

Dynamic Volt-Watt Gradient.  Signed quantity that establishes the ratio of additional Watts supplied (expressed in terms of % DRCT.WMax) to the present difference from the moving average voltage (expressed as % DRCT.VRef).
Dynamic Volt-Watt Filter Time.  The time in seconds used to calculate the "moving average voltage for dynamic Volt-Watt support."

Dynamic Volt-Watt Lower Deadband. Percentage of the nominal voltage (DRCT.Vref) measured below the. moving average voltage.  If the present voltage is above this value no  additional Watts shall be supplied.

Dynamic Volt-Watt Upper Deadband. Percentage of the nominal voltage (DRCT.Vref) measured above the moving average voltage.  If the present voltage is below this value no additional Watts shall be supplied.
Dynamic Volt-Watt Attempted Output. Watt output that the mode is attempting to achieve based on the Voltage  input and other parameters.
Frequency-Watt Frequency Reference Input.  Frequency measurement read from the meter and used as an input to the mode.
Frequency-Watt High Starting Frequency.  Delta frequency between start frequency and nominal grid frequency for high frequency events.
Frequency-Watt High Stopping Frequency. Delta frequency between stop frequency and nominal grid frequency for high frequency events.

Frequency-Watt High Discharging /Generating Gradient.  Signed quantity that establishes the ratio of additional Watts supplied (expressed in terms of % DRCT.WMax) to the present difference from the moving average frequency (expressed as % of nominal grid frequency).
Frequency-Watt High Charging Gradient.  Ratio of additional Watts charged to the present difference from the moving average frequency
Frequency-Watt Low Starting Frequency.  Delta frequency between start frequency and nominal grid frequency for low frequency events.
Frequency-Watt Low Stopping Frequency.  Delta frequency between stop frequency and nominal grid frequency for low frequency events.

Frequency-Watt Low Discharging / Generating Gradient.  Signed unit-less quantity that establishes the ratio of additional Watts supplied (expressed in terms of % DRCT.WMax) to the present difference from the moving average frequency (expressed as % of nominal grid frequency).
Frequency-Watt Low Charging Gradient.  Ratio of additional Watts charged to the present difference from the moving average frequency
Frequency-Watt Start Delay. Intentional delay before function activation for a frequency event
Frequency-Watt Stop Delay. Intentional delay before stoping the function after a fequency event
Frequency-Watt Ramp Up Time Constant. Time constant or open loop response time for moving from the current active power target to a higher active power target.
Frequency-Watt Ramp Down Time Constant. Time constant or open loop response time for moving from the current active power target ot a higher active power target.

Frequency-Watt Attempted Output. Watt output thhat the mode is attempting to achieve based on the Frequency input and other parameters. If a Snapshot of Power is not enabled: this is the maximum active power the outstation will attempt to generate or absorb.
Active Power Limit Enabling Time Window. Time window (in seconds) within which to randomly execute a command. If the time window is zero the command will be execute immediately
Active Power Limit Enabling Ramp Time. Ramp time in seconds for moving from current operational mode settings to new operational mode settings

Active Power Limit Reversion Timeout Period. Reversion Timeout Period (in seconds) after which the device will revert to its default status such as closing the switch to reconnect to the grid or allowing maximum watts output in case communications are lost or mitigating messages are not received
Active Power Limit Signal Meter ID
Active Power Limit Reference Input. Active Power measurement read from the meter and used as an input to the mode.
Active Power Limit Charge Setpoint. Limit of imported Watts as a percentage of Maximum Active Power capability
Active Power Limit Generation Setpoint. Limit of exported Watts as a percentage of Maximum Active Power capability
Charge/Discharge Enabling Ramp Time. Ramp time in seconds for moving from current operational mode settings to new operational mode settings
Charge/Discharge Active Power Target.  Percentage of maximum active power.
Charge/Discharge Ramp Up Time Constant. Time constant or open loop response time for moving from the current active power target to a higher active power target.
Charge/Discharge Ramp Down Time Constant. Time constant or open loop response time for moving from the current active power target to a higher active power target.
Charge/Discharge Minimum Reserve for Storage. The reserve level below which the storage system may be only be discharged in emergency situations expressed as a percentage of the usable capacity.
Charge/Discharge Maximum Reserve for Storage. The reserve level above which the storage system may be only be charged in emergency situations expressed as a percentage of the usable capacity.
Coordinated Charge/Discharge Enabling Ramp Time. Ramp time in seconds for moving from current operational mode settings to new operational mode settings.
Coordinated Charge/Discharge Target State of Charge. Charge that the system is expected to achieve as a percentage of the usable capacity.
Coordinated Charge/Discharge Target Date. Date by which the storage system must reach the target SOC. Days since January 1 1970 UTC.
Coordinated Charge/Discharge Target Time. Time by when the storage system must reach the target SOC. Expressed as thhe number of seconds since the start of Target Date.
Coordinated Charge/Discharge Energy Request. Amount of energy that must be transferred from the grid to the charger to move the SOC from the value at the specific time of reference to the target SOC.
Coordinated Charge/Discharge Minimum Charging Duration. Minimum duration to move from the Soc at the time of reference to the target SOC.
Coordinated Charge/Discharge Date of Reference. Date that the SOC is measured or computed by the storage system and is the basis for the Energy Request Minimum Charging Duration and other parameters.
Coordinated Charge/Discharge Time of Reference.  Time that the SOC is measured or computed by the storage system and is the basis for the Energy Request Minimum Charging Duration and other parameters
Coordinated Charge/Discharge Duration at Maximum Charge Rate. Duration that energy can be stored at the Maximum Charge Rate.
Coordinated Charge/Discharge Duration Maximum Discharge Rate. Duration that energy can be delivered at the Maximum Discharge Rate.

Active Power Response Mode #1 Enabling Ramp Time
Active Power Response Mode #1 Reversion Timeout Period

AGC Time Constant Ramp Up Time. Ramp time in seconds for moving from the current active power target to a higher active power target.
AGC Time Constant Ramp Down Time. Ramp time in seconds for moving from the current active power target to a lower active power target.
AGC Minimum Usable SOC.  This is a range specific to AGC because the DER may be using the rest of the usable capacity for something else. Read-only.
AGC Maximum Usable SOC. This is a range specific to AGC because the DER may be using the rest of the usable capacity for something else. Read-only.
AGC Expected State of Charge Time Interval
Active Power Smoothing Enabling Time Window
Active Power Smoothing Enabling Ramp Time
Active Power Smoothing Reversion Timeout Period
Active Power Smoothing Signal Meter ID
Active Power Smoothing Reference Power Input.  Active Power measurement read from the meter and used as an input to the mode.

Active Power Smoothing Gradient. Signed quantity that establishes the ratio of additional smoothing Watts provided to the present delta-watts of the reference load or generation. Delta Watts is the difference between the moving average  and the present value of the reference power.  Positive values of this gradient are for following load (increased reference load results in a dynamic increase in DER output) and negative values are for following generation (increased reference generation results in a dynamic decrease in DER output).
Active Power Smoothing Lower Limit. Difference in Watts from the moving average of the reference power above which no smoothing shall be applied.
Active Power Smoothing Upper Limit. Difference in Watts from the moving average of the reference power below which no smoothing shall be applied.
Active Power Smoothing Filter Time (sec). Time in seconds used to calculate the moving average of the reference load or generation being smoothed.
Active Power Smoothing Discharge Ramp Up Rate. The maximum generation ramp up rate expressed as a percentage of the Maximum Generation Rate (WMax) per second.
Active Power Smoothing Discharge Ramp Down Rate. The maximum generation ramp down rate expressed as a percentage of the Maximum Generation Rate (WMax) per second.
Active Power Smoothing Charge Ramp Up Rate.  The maximum charging ramp up rate expressed as a percentage of the Maximum Charging Rate (WChaMax) per second.
Active Power Smoothing Charge Ramp Down Rate. The maximum charging ramp down rate expressed as a percentage of the Maximum Charnging Rate (WChaMax) per second.
Active Power Smoothing Attempted Output.  Watt output that the mode is attempting to achieve based on the Watt input and other parameters.
Volt-Watt Reference Voltage Input. Voltage measurement read from the meter and used as an input to the mode.
Volt-Watt Curve Index.  Index of the Volt-Watt curve that should be used by the mode.
Volt-Watt Attempted Output. Maximum active power the outstation will attempt to generate or absorb based on the Voltage input and selected curve.
Volt-Watt Discharging Ramp Up Rate. Maximum ramp up rate.
Volt-Watt Discharging Ramp Down Rate. Maximum ramp down rate.
Volt-Watt Charging Ramp Up Rate. Maximum charging ramp up rate.
Volt-Watt Charging Ramp Down Rate. Maximum charging ramp down rate.
Frequency-Watt Curve Frequency Reference Input.  Frequency measurement read from the meter and used as an input to the mode.
Frequency-Watt Curve - Curve Index. Index of the Frequency-Watt curve that should be used by the mode.
Frequency-Watt Curve - High Frequency Hysteresis Curve Index
Frequency-Watt Curve - Lo Frequency Hysteresis Curve Index
Frequency-Watt Curve Start Delay. Intentional delay before function activation for a frequency event
Frequency-Watt Curve Stop Delay. Intentional delay before stopping the function after a fequency event
Frequency-Watt Curve Ramp Up Time Constant. Time constant or open loop response time for moving from th current active power target to a higher active power target.
Frequency-Watt Curve Ramp Down Time Constant. Time constant or open loop response time for moving from the current active power target to a higher active power target.
Frequency-Watt Curve Discharge Ramp Up Rate
Frequency-Watt Curve Discharge Ramp Down Rate

Frequency-Watt Curve Charge Ramp Down Rate

Frequency-Watt Curve Attempted Output. Watt output that the mode is attempting to achieve based on the Frequency input and selected curve. If “Snapshot of Power” is not enabled: this is the maximum active power the outstation will attempt to generate or absorbs.
Constant VArs Enabling Ramp Time. Ramp time in seconds for moving from current operational mode settings to new operational mode settings.
Constant VArs Reactive Power Target. Percentage of maximum reactive power.

Constant VArs Ramp Down Time Constant

Fixed Power Factor Enabling Ramp Time

Volt-VAr Control Adjusted Reference Voltage.  The Voltage used as reference for Volt-VAr control.  If Autonomous Voltage Reference Adjustment is disabled this is the same fixed value as the Reference Voltage.
Volt-VAr Curve Index.  Index of the Volt-VAr curve that should be used by the mode.
Volt-VAr Autonomous Voltage Reference Adjustment Time Constant
Volt-VAr Attempted Output.  Var output that the mode is attempting to achieve based on the Voltage input and selected curve.
Watt-VAr Reference Power Input. Power measurement read from the meter and used as an input to the mode.
Watt-VAr Curve Index.  Index of the Watt-VAr curve that should be used by the mode.
Watt-VAr Attempted Output.  Var output that the mode is attempting to achieve based on the Watt input and selected curve.
